1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,276
Hello, friends!

2
00:00:01,276 --> 00:00:03,776
Picture yourself on a ship at sea,

3
00:00:03,776 --> 00:00:07,250
relishing the fresh and invigorating sea breeze.

4
00:00:07,250 --> 00:00:10,023
Suddenly, a remarkable sight unfolds before you

5
00:00:14,789 --> 00:00:17,821
a colossal missile emerges from the water.

6
00:00:17,821 --> 00:00:19,522
Not just any missile,

7
00:00:19,522 --> 00:00:21,655
but a nuclear missile

8
00:00:21,655 --> 00:00:25,100
with the capability to reach a target 
on the other side of the globe,

9
00:00:25,100 --> 00:00:26,652
spanning thousands of kilometers.

10
00:00:26,652 --> 00:00:28,282
This isn't a mere imagination;

11
00:00:28,282 --> 00:00:31,158
it's a reality today, thanks to submarines.

12
00:00:31,158 --> 00:00:32,786
The footage you just witnessed

13
00:00:32,786 --> 00:00:36,550
was a test of a Trident 2 missile 
conducted by the US Navy,

14
00:00:36,550 --> 00:00:40,431
launched from a US Ohio-class submarine.

15
00:00:40,431 --> 00:00:42,340
The Trident 2 falls under the category of

16
00:00:42,340 --> 00:00:46,006
submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs),

17
00:00:46,006 --> 00:00:48,792
representing one of the most formidable weapons globally.

18
00:00:48,792 --> 00:00:53,195
These SLBMs boast an estimated yield of 475 kilotons,

19
00:00:53,195 --> 00:00:59,243
a stark contrast to the 12-13 kiloton yield of 
the nuclear bomb dropped on Hiroshima.

20
00:00:59,243 --> 00:01:00,832
Presently, these potent weapons

21
00:01:00,832 --> 00:01:02,258
are housed within submarines,

22
00:01:02,258 --> 00:01:05,408
stealthily traversing the world's oceans

23
00:01:05,408 --> 00:01:08,237
in highly classified, undisclosed locations.

24
00:01:08,237 --> 00:01:11,470
In today's video, let's delve into 
the intricacies of these submarines

25
00:01:11,470 --> 00:01:13,538
understanding the technology that propels them

26
00:01:13,538 --> 00:01:15,867
and unravelling their operational mechanisms.

27
00:01:27,769 --> 00:01:30,807
Fundamentally, all submarines operate based on

28
00:01:30,807 --> 00:01:33,126
Archimedes' principle,

29
00:01:33,126 --> 00:01:36,205
a concept likely familiar from school.

30
00:01:36,205 --> 00:01:38,416
As an object sinks,

31
00:01:38,416 --> 00:01:41,731
it experiences a buoyant force

32
00:01:41,731 --> 00:01:46,390
equivalent to the weight of the fluid displaced

33
00:01:46,390 --> 00:01:48,038
due to this object's sinking.

34
00:01:48,038 --> 00:01:52,057
When a submarine's weight 
matches that of the water it displaces,

35
00:01:52,057 --> 00:01:54,633
it achieves a level of neutral buoyancy.

36
00:01:54,633 --> 00:01:57,596
Allowing it to maintain a constant depth.

37
00:01:57,596 --> 00:01:59,892
When the objective is to submerge,

38
00:01:59,892 --> 00:02:02,817
the gravitational force applied must exceed

39
00:02:02,817 --> 00:02:03,759
the buoyant force,

40
00:02:03,759 --> 00:02:07,125
prompting the use of ballast tanks.

41
00:02:07,125 --> 00:02:10,491
Typically, these two tanks are located at the submarine's ends,

42
00:02:10,491 --> 00:02:13,733
they are filled with air at the surface,

43
00:02:13,733 --> 00:02:15,530
enabling the vessel to float.

44
00:02:15,530 --> 00:02:17,020
To descend into the water,

45
00:02:17,020 --> 00:02:19,598
these ballast tanks are flooded with water,

46
00:02:19,598 --> 00:02:21,188
increasing the submarine's weight

47
00:02:21,188 --> 00:02:23,004
and initiating the descent.

48
00:02:23,004 --> 00:02:25,971
Such scenarios are labelled to have negative buoyancy.

49
00:02:25,971 --> 00:02:28,859
It indicates the control of a submarine's depth

50
00:02:28,859 --> 00:02:31,714
by adjusting the water level in its ballast tanks.

51
00:02:31,714 --> 00:02:34,524
This mechanism governs vertical 
movement for ascending and descending.

52
00:02:34,524 --> 00:02:36,775
For lateral movement, 
such as turning sideways in the water,

53
00:02:36,775 --> 00:02:39,388
a Rudder is employed.

54
00:02:39,388 --> 00:02:41,096
It looks like this.

55
00:02:41,096 --> 00:02:43,208
It is known as a Vertical Rudder.

56
00:02:43,208 --> 00:02:46,648
This facilitates horizontal movement in the water.

57
00:02:46,648 --> 00:02:50,480
Similar rudders are used in boats, ships, and aircraft.

58
00:02:50,480 --> 00:02:54,298
Additionally, forward and backward motion 
is achieved through the use of a propeller,

59
00:02:54,298 --> 00:02:56,320
essentially a fan.

60
00:02:59,849 --> 00:03:01,681
While navigating underwater,

61
00:03:01,681 --> 00:03:03,542
a reliable means of orientation is essential.

62
00:03:03,542 --> 00:03:06,030
Sonar technology serves this purpose.

63
00:03:06,030 --> 00:03:09,840
It operates based on sound.

64
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:12,366
There are two main types of sonar technologies:

65
00:03:12,366 --> 00:03:14,448
active sonar and passive sonar.

66
00:03:14,448 --> 00:03:17,486
Active sonar involves emitting sound from the submarine.

67
00:03:17,486 --> 00:03:20,334
The sound travels through the water,

68
00:03:20,334 --> 00:03:24,156
collides with objects, and upon 
reflection back to the submarine,

69
00:03:24,156 --> 00:03:27,094
the time and distance calculations

70
00:03:27,094 --> 00:03:30,882
provide information about the submarine's 
location and the surrounding environment.

71
00:03:30,882 --> 00:03:33,723
In contrast, passive sonar does not emit sound

72
00:03:33,723 --> 00:03:36,960
but rather detects sounds from other 
sources, such as enemy submarines,

73
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:41,305
by listening to their engine and propeller noises 

74
00:03:41,305 --> 00:03:44,952
to determine their distance.

75
00:03:44,952 --> 00:03:48,785
However, the use of sonar technology 
has adverse effects on marine life,

76
00:03:48,785 --> 00:03:50,872
impacting creatures like whales and dolphins,

77
00:03:50,872 --> 00:03:54,638
which also rely on sonar for communication.

78
00:03:54,638 --> 00:03:59,261
To address this concern, some submarines 
are exploring alternative technologies

79
00:03:59,261 --> 00:04:01,250
such as LiDAR,

80
00:04:01,250 --> 00:04:03,501
Light Detection and Ranging.

81
00:04:03,501 --> 00:04:07,229
LiDAR employs light to estimate distance

82
00:04:07,229 --> 00:04:11,059
and is already integrated into many modern smartphones.

83
00:04:11,059 --> 00:04:13,484
Another alternative is using RADAR

84
00:04:13,484 --> 00:04:15,603
Radio Detection and Ranging,

85
00:04:15,603 --> 00:04:18,899
it is effective above water and in aircrafts

86
00:04:18,899 --> 00:04:21,952
which utilizes radio waves to calculate distances.

87
00:04:21,952 --> 00:04:28,201
but is limited underwater due to the 
restricted transmission of radio waves.

88
00:04:28,201 --> 00:04:31,103
Lastly, emerging technologies are being 
explored as potential alternatives like

89
00:04:31,103 --> 00:04:34,337
MRS 
Magnetic Anomaly Detection System

90
00:04:34,337 --> 00:04:36,019
or Gravitational Anomaly Detection System.

91
00:04:36,019 --> 00:04:39,364
However, the bottom line is that today,

92
00:04:39,364 --> 00:04:41,385
the predominant technology employed 
in submarines is Sonar.

93
00:04:41,385 --> 00:04:46,286
Multiple Sonar sensors are strategically 
installed around submarines

94
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:49,330
to continuously collect and monitor data,

95
00:04:49,330 --> 00:04:53,266
ensuring there are no obstacles or hazards in their path.

96
