The link is in the description.

132
00:06:40,218 --> 00:06:41,831
Now, turning our attention to military submarines.

133
00:06:41,831 --> 00:06:44,873
The topmost deck of a military submarine 
is typically outfitted with torpedoes,

134
00:06:44,873 --> 00:06:46,511
which serve as weapons.

135
00:06:46,511 --> 00:06:48,466
The lowest deck houses battery rooms

136
00:06:48,466 --> 00:06:50,487
that supply electricity to the submarine,

137
00:06:50,487 --> 00:06:52,917
and sandwiched in between are the diesel machine,

138
00:06:52,917 --> 00:06:57,153
motor room, and the nerve center 
known as the control room.

139
00:06:57,153 --> 00:07:00,465
Positioned above the control room, 
you'll usually find a conning tower

140
00:07:00,465 --> 00:07:03,813
an essential component serving as 
the submarine's attack center.

141
00:07:03,813 --> 00:07:05,761
The conning tower is equipped with various instruments,

142
00:07:05,761 --> 00:07:09,704
including periscopes for observing the surroundings,

143
00:07:09,704 --> 00:07:12,870
electronic antennas, and access points for arms.

144
00:07:12,870 --> 00:07:17,779
It also serves as the main entry and exit point

145
00:07:17,779 --> 00:07:21,478
for individuals entering or leaving the submarine.

146
00:07:21,478 --> 00:07:24,366
Torpedoes are stored in torpedo tubes.

147
00:07:24,366 --> 00:07:27,701
These are basically self-propelled underwater missiles.

148
00:07:27,701 --> 00:07:31,841
These tubes are cylindrical containers 
designed to house these cylindrical missiles.

149
00:07:35,870 --> 00:07:39,630
In modern submarines, torpedoes 
are typically placed at the front.

150
00:07:39,630 --> 00:07:43,685
However, in the 2017 Bollywood film 'Ghazi Attack,'

151
00:07:43,685 --> 00:07:48,414
the depiction of a submarine featured 
torpedoes at both the front and back.

152
00:07:48,414 --> 00:07:51,819
This was historically accurate as powerful submarines back then

153
00:07:51,819 --> 00:07:54,276
indeed had torpedoes at both ends

154
00:07:54,276 --> 00:07:57,680
because torpedoes could only travel 
in a straight line at the time.

155
00:08:02,341 --> 00:08:04,073
An intriguing aspect is that

156
00:08:04,073 --> 00:08:08,417
these torpedo tubes can also be used as 
emergency escape routes from submarines.

157
00:08:08,417 --> 00:08:11,543
Nevertheless, escaping through them is no easy feat.

158
00:08:11,543 --> 00:08:17,197
The tubes have a narrow diameter, 
measuring only 12.75 inches for light torpedoes

159
00:08:17,197 --> 00:08:20,092
and 21 inches for heavy torpedoes.

160
00:08:20,092 --> 00:08:21,730
First of all, this is an extremely narrow space.

161
00:08:21,730 --> 00:08:25,063
Additionally, individuals attempting to escape 
must wear a 23 kg escape

162
00:08:25,063 --> 00:08:27,487
suit due to the immense water pressure at those depths.

163
00:08:27,487 --> 00:08:31,926
One can't simply exit the submarine at those depths.

164
00:08:31,926 --> 00:08:34,544
The immense pressure of the water 
would crush the unprepared instantly.

165
00:08:34,544 --> 00:08:36,988
Officers working in submarines

166
00:08:36,988 --> 00:08:39,859
undergo rigorous training for six months.

167
00:08:44,994 --> 00:08:47,962
India's sole military submarine training establishment,

168
00:08:47,962 --> 00:08:52,322
INS Satavahana, 
is located in Vishakhapatnam city.

169
00:08:52,322 --> 00:08:55,794
At this training facility, numerous replicas 
of torpedo tubes are available

170
00:08:55,794 --> 00:08:59,202
for officers to practice emergency escapes.

171
00:08:59,202 --> 00:09:00,715
Now, let's delve into the submarine's power source

172
00:09:00,715 --> 00:09:03,041
where does it get the energy to operate?

173
00:09:03,041 --> 00:09:05,362
The answer depends on the type of submarine,

174
00:09:05,362 --> 00:09:07,842
with two primary categories in India:

175
00:09:07,842 --> 00:09:10,134
conventional submarines and nuclear submarines.

176
00:09:10,134 --> 00:09:14,177
Conventional submarines utilize large electrical batteries,

177
00:09:14,177 --> 00:09:21,193
akin to car batteries, but these 
require recharging every 2-3 days.

178
00:09:21,193 --> 00:09:23,193
To recharge these batteries,

179
00:09:23,193 --> 00:09:24,966
a diesel engine is needed.

180
00:09:24,966 --> 00:09:27,799
However, operating a diesel engine

181
00:09:27,799 --> 00:09:30,271
necessitates oxygen from the air.

182
00:09:30,271 --> 00:09:33,632
Since submarines operate underwater,

183
00:09:33,632 --> 00:09:41,676
they must resurface to run the 
diesel engine and recharge the batteries.

184
00:09:45,126 --> 00:09:47,916
In contrast, nuclear submarines don't have this problem. 

185
00:09:47,916 --> 00:09:53,517
They employ a nuclear reactor instead 
of a diesel engine to generate electricity.

186
00:09:53,517 --> 00:09:57,237
This allows them to remain submerged for extended periods,

187
00:09:57,237 --> 00:10:00,334
limited only by the human factors,

188
00:10:00,334 --> 00:10:03,248
such as the availability of food 
and provisions for the crew.

189
00:10:03,248 --> 00:10:07,923
The submarines can remained submerged 
as long as there's sufficient provisions for the crew.

190
00:10:07,923 --> 00:10:10,068
Examining the structure of a submarine,

191
00:10:10,068 --> 00:10:13,607
the outer layer is typically composed of rubber.

192
00:10:13,607 --> 00:10:15,262
This reason for strategic choice is quite simple actually.

193
00:10:15,262 --> 00:10:18,223
Because rubber effectively absorbs sound,

194
00:10:18,223 --> 00:10:21,855
making it challenging to detect submarines in the water.

195
00:10:21,855 --> 00:10:24,290
Military submarines are designed to be elusive,

196
00:10:24,290 --> 00:10:27,906
ensuring they are not easily spotted by enemy counterparts.

197
00:10:27,906 --> 00:10:31,563
The black layer visible in submarine photos

198
00:10:31,563 --> 00:10:32,992
is made of rubber.

199
00:10:32,992 --> 00:10:35,436
Moving to the interior, the primary body 
of the submarine within the rubber layer

200
00:10:35,436 --> 00:10:36,831
is referred to as the Hull.

201
00:10:36,831 --> 00:10:38,796
There are two common types of hulls:

202
00:10:38,796 --> 00:10:40,877
single hull and double hull.

203
00:10:40,877 --> 00:10:44,380
Single hull submarines have only one layer of the main body,

204
00:10:44,380 --> 00:10:47,238
while double hull submarines consist of two layers of the main body.

205
00:10:47,238 --> 00:10:48,748
In the double hull design,

206
00:10:48,748 --> 00:10:51,488
the ballast tank is integrated,

207
00:10:51,488 --> 00:10:53,811
with water filling the space between the two layers,

208
00:10:53,811 --> 00:10:56,500
effectively serving as a ballast tank.

209
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:58,518
The clear advantage of a double hull configuration

210
00:10:58,518 --> 00:11:00,546
lies in providing an additional layer of protection.

211
00:11:00,546 --> 00:11:02,045
In the event of a collision,

212
00:11:02,045 --> 00:11:03,668
a double hull submarine offers enhanced security.

213
00:11:03,668 --> 00:11:05,588
Most modern military submarines

214
00:11:05,588 --> 00:11:07,815
adopt the double hull design,

215
00:11:07,815 --> 00:11:10,403
not only for added protection 
but also to better withstand water pressure

216
00:11:10,403 --> 00:11:12,054
as illustrated by the incident involving the Titan submersible's

217
00:11:12,054 --> 00:11:14,930
implosion under water pressure.

218
00:11:14,930 --> 00:11:18,272
At the water's surface, the atmospheric pressure is 1 atmosphere,

219
00:11:18,272 --> 00:11:21,351
equivalent to 1 kilogram per square centimeter.

220
00:11:21,351 --> 00:11:24,306
As one descends underwater, pressure increases.

221
00:11:24,306 --> 00:11:26,152
For every 10 meters of depth,

222
00:11:26,152 --> 00:11:28,488
there's an additional 1 kilogram per square meter of pressure.

223
00:11:28,488 --> 00:11:34,641
Military submarines are typically designed 
to operate at depths of 300-400 meters,

224
00:11:34,641 --> 00:11:38,314
with some capable of reaching depths of 500 meters.

225
00:11:38,314 --> 00:11:41,714
At this depth, the pressure reaches 50 atmospheres

226
00:11:41,714 --> 00:11:44,437
50 times greater than at the surface.

227
00:11:44,437 --> 00:11:48,208
Obviously, constructing submarine 
hulls requires robust materials.

228
00:11:48,208 --> 00:11:50,717
Not using the right materials

229
00:11:50,717 --> 00:11:52,589
might cause failures or accidents. 

230
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:54,658
As with the Titan submersible.

231
00:11:55,764 --> 00:11:59,759
Military submarines use high-quality steel alloys,

232
00:11:59,759 --> 00:12:04,725
blending steel with titanium, carbon, 
aluminium, and other elements.

233
00:12:04,725 --> 00:12:07,511
The complexity of designing a submarine is underscored

234
00:12:07,511 --> 00:12:11,602
by the fact that it takes approximately 
10 years to design a diesel-electric submarine,

235
00:12:11,602 --> 00:12:16,420
while a nuclear submarine demands a 
minimum of 15-17 years at the designing stage.

236
00:12:16,420 --> 00:12:21,160
This intricacy is why India often outsources submarine design

237
00:12:21,160 --> 00:12:27,413
to other countries, such as Russia, Germany, or France.

238
00:12:27,413 --> 00:12:30,585
However, India manufactures its own submarines.

239
00:12:30,585 --> 00:12:34,101
India's first domestically manufactured 
submarine was INS Shalki,

240
00:12:34,101 --> 00:12:39,234
launched in 1987 during 
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's tenure.

241
00:12:39,234 --> 00:12:43,173
and commissioned by the Indian Navy in 1992.

242
00:12:43,173 --> 00:12:46,005
On Indian Navy's website, you will see that

243
00:12:46,005 --> 00:12:48,919
there are different categories of submarines,

244
00:12:48,919 --> 00:12:50,745
which are divided into classes.

245
00:12:50,745 --> 00:12:52,586
In India, there are four classes.

246
00:12:52,586 --> 00:12:57,665
Sindhughosh, Shishumar, Kalvari, and Arihant.

247
00:12:57,665 --> 00:12:59,653
The first three classes

248
00:12:59,653 --> 00:13:01,545
are of conventional submarines:

249
00:13:01,545 --> 00:13:04,741
the Sindhughosh class comprises Russian diesel-powered EKMs,

250
00:13:04,741 --> 00:13:08,289
the Shishumar class features German SSKs,

251
00:13:08,289 --> 00:13:12,812
and the Kalvari class showcases new French-designed and Indian-built SCORPENEs.

